The stages filter should work just like the other filters and not just hide the column.

!hc_635.jpg|thumbnail!

I would expect, that line #7 wouldn't be shown after selecting the "Design" stage filter.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1666].
  {panel}

This would allow me to organize my Stories by Epic.  It would be sweeter if there was a way to drill down through initiatives, epics, stories then sub-tasks but I'll take the quick win of just being able to organize my stories by epic.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1625].
  {panel}

Currently, in Portfolio for JIRA, you are able to toggle between the Story, Epic and higher hierarchical levels on the scope and schedule view. This is very useful, but for Epics and other parent issues that do not have a continuous schedule of implementing work underneath it, it can sometimes be misleading not being able to drill down to the child issues on the schedule view.
For example, an Epic may have one story in sprint 1 (a spike) and all it's remaining stories in sprints 20, 21 and 22, but the Epic schedule view will just show a single bar starting in sprint 1 and ending in sprint 22. It would be very useful if you could visualise the underlying work in some way, either by having the option to expand and view the child issues on the schedule, or by shading/adjusting the thickness of the issue bar to illustrate where the underlying work actually is.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1653].
  {panel}

The option for the assignee to be updated from the members field in portfolio doesn't seem to work both ways - it works from JIRA Portfolio to JIRA but not JIRA to Portfolio. Therefore it is required that any changes to the assignee in JIRA are tracked and updated manually in JIRA Portfolio, this is time consuming for plans with a lot of tickets.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1335].
  {panel}

Now it is possible to rank a story with drag'n drop but it is not possible to drag them into an epic. 

The feeling when you use the system is that it should be possible, and it would be a nice feature to have.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1370].
  {panel}

To export a Plan as an CSV file so the information originated in a Plan could be used outside of the application.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1580].
  {panel}

While it is possible to see total hours (as well as a percentage and hours completed) for any ticket within the plan hierarchy, there does not appear to be a way to see this rolled up information for the entire project.

The only work-around that I can think of is to add a new top-level ticket type in the hierarchy, and have that be the sole top-level ticket for a give project. However, that seems like a poor use of the hierarchy feature, and adds an extra level just for one simple purpose.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
