  {panel}

To separate and track different deliverables from a single project.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1521].
  {panel}

I want to plan a single stream to be completed by a team so each work item starts after the completion of the previous work item, following rank order. 

h2. Workaround
Using dependencies however for a large scale plan this isn't practical as it requires setting up dependencies for every item in the plan which is very time consuming.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1389].
  {panel}

It would be great to have the ability to auto assign issues to members who already worked on the task.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1803].
  {panel}

When i click on an epic, not much happens beyond telling me the epic Key.

I would like to see which Initiative it belongs to, and for that matter, which Stories are a part of the epic.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1446].
  {panel}

One of our customer wants to have the ability to define quantity limited resources in Portfolio and assign them to an issue so that when Portfolio calculate the plan it can take account of the available resources, if a required resource for an issue is not available then the issue will be pushed off.
One trivial scenario : 3 employees work on three 1 man-days issues and each issue requires a workstation for employee to work on, customer has only 2 workstations available, so in this case it should take two days to finish the work instead of just one day.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1443].
  {panel}

Standard plans allow three different metrics to evaluate progress.
It would be very important to enable the same metrics in Live plans, too.

As far as I see, currently the only option is the so-called "Time spent". This is not good for us, as we do not recommend teams to track time using the time spent but rather original/remaining estimate.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-501].
  {panel}

It would be useful to have an additional grouping option in the capacity report of Portfolio for Stages/Skills.
This would allow the user to see free capacity (number of hours) per skill along the timeline and then be able  to spot bottlenecks and re-plan to better use resources

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1399].
  {panel}

The commit section is not intuitive in regards to clicking the issue key to see what the change is - we expected this to link us to the issue in JIRA so did not pick up that we could view the change until we watched the video. Perhaps have a link next to each ticket on the commit screen to "view change" rather than the user clicking the key?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1599].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1512].
  {panel}

In our workflow we create sub-tasks 'types' that line up to skills, eg Software Design/Development/Test. When importing a board of the parent issues it becomes a large manual task to sync the sub-tasks types to the related skill column (eg 20+ issues with 4 sub-tasks each = 80 changes).

Having a configuration point in the portfolio store a default mapping to 'type to skill' will quickly solve this and allow the plan to accurately track the projected finish dates. This mapping should also apply upon creation of new sub tasks in the portfolio view, etc.

At the moment the portfolio can't be used by a large number of our teams due to this usability issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1392].
  {panel}

At the moment, in case too many backlog items are manually assigned to a release with a fixed end date, the release date gets pushed back and makes the release show up as overbooked and in red. However, the issues that don't fit in are scheduled after the fixed release date.

In some cases customers want to have all manually assigned items to be scheduled before the fixed release date and hence cause the respective sprints / Kanban weeks of that release to be overbooked (i.e., a similar behaviour as we have at the moment when manually assign items to a sprint but on a release level).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1608].
  {panel}

When creating new stories on a Plan, it would be helpful to have an option to enable the inheritance of some values - especially Team and Theme - from the parent issues according to Hierarchy.

Today, these fields are empty by default, which could cause confusion when using filters.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1763].
  {panel}

Currently there is no integration between JPO and Tempo plugin. It would be great if we could somehow implement certain degree of integration to Tempo since there is any quite a number of customer which is using JPO and Tempo at the same time.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1870].
  {panel}

As an administrator, I think it would be beneficial to allow for bulk updates in Portfolio live plans, such as allowing a user to update members/teams for all epics and stories under a specific release. I'm not aware of a mechanism currently in place for this, but it might be worth looking into.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1390].
  {panel}

Currently when committing a live plan, issue assignments made by the scheduling algorithm are not saved to JIRA's assignee field. This suggestion is to add the ability to update the assignee on issues when committing.

Note that manual issue assignments _can_ be committed to JIRA, if the *Commit issue assignee* plan configuration option is enabled. This suggestion is about committing automatic/scheduled assignments to JIRA.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1783].
  {panel}

As a user I want to filter on issue status so I can see which stories still need definition or area ready for prioritization.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1050].
  {panel}

Hello,
After we "complete" an Initiative (or Epic, or Story) in Portfolio, it would be super useful that the Start and End dates be kept for reference purpose. This way I could easily consult my historical data and quickly view which project started/ended when.

Thanks.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1621].
  {panel}

Relates to JPO-1218 and JPO-83

A 'plan-of-plans' view should be available that pulls together scheduling information from multiple plans, possibly as a read-only report.
This would be invaluable not only to view dependencies between plans (see JPO-1218 and JPO-83) but also to view and compare higher-level shared information between the plans e.g. if teams share releases and initiatives.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1840].
  {panel}

As a plan owner, I would like to know about any stories within the scope of my plan which is marked as blocked by an issue outside of my plan because those blockers need to be resolved before my plan is accurate.

We have one project per team, and are further organized around either platform or application. Our application teams has milestones and releases and would like to use JIRA Portfolio to plan and manage them. However, many of their features are dependent on the development or fixing of underlying platform work, which would not appear on their plan.

It would be nice if Portfolio could do some scheduling or other logic around these "external" dependencies, but at the very least I need a report or list of the stories outside of my plan which are blocking stories within so that I can run them down, get timing, etc.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1268].
  {panel}

Currently when a story is under one Epic, and then in JIRA Agile someone changes the Epic Link to that story, someone has to go into JIRA Portfolio and manually move that story to the new Epic. It would be helpful to provide an auto-sync option where moving what Epic a Story is under is automatically synced from JIRA Agile to Portfolio for JIRA and vice versa.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1325].
  {panel}

h5. Problem Statement

Currently, it's not possible to view on the UI (because it's not stored on the database as well) who created a plan on JIRA Portfolio. It could be useful for JIRA Administrators to be able to see who created the plans for better tracking.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1198].
  {panel}

Currently, the first story created under an epic will be assigned to the epic's release. For subsequent stories created under the epic though, this is not the case. It would be more consistent if all stories created under an epic were automatically assigned to the release of the epic.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1371].
  {panel}

Currently Portfolio supports only one type of dependency which is "B can start as soon as A is completed". 

Add support for other dependencies such as Start to Finish, Finish to Finish, Start to Start, Finish to Start, or a partial overlap such as "can start when 50% is completed"

Additionally, support configuration to set the delay such as number of days before the start of another Epic/Story.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1320].
  {panel}

On the page [Story points|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiraportfoliocloud/story-points-715263898.html] there is a link for "Adding a new team member when estimating in story points" under *How will the velocity of a team be affected when adding a new team member?* which redirects to https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiraportfoliocloud/story-points-715263898.html, which is the same page. 

It should re-direct to [Settings estimates with story points|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiraportfoliocloud/settings-estimates-with-story-points-715263380.html] specifically the section *Adding a new team member when estimating in story points*

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1269].
  {panel}

As a user when I am in the backlog looking at the Scheduling pane at the bottom of the screen, if I highlight/select an issue in the view I should either automatically be brought to the place in the Portfolio backlog where that issue is, or provided a link "go to" or "view" that when clicked allows me to see that issue in the Portfolio backlog. 

Please see attached image for a visual.
Thanks.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1829].
  {panel}

Currently while going through the motions of creating a plan, the UI shows releases that are out the door and still in the project.  This becomes a pain to look for the new ones you want to create the plan for.  The only way to not show is to archive that release in the project but that will prevent from adding that version to affects version(s) field for any new issues coming from a customer or reported internally.

It would be great if there is a switch to show only unreleased versions in LP or it automatically removes them from the UI during plan creation.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1503].
  {panel}

This would look pretty similar to the hierarchical view on the “Scope” tab of Portfolio. In addition, I should be able to automatically select all children of an issue by selecting the parent (i.e., I select an epic to commit and all its child issues are automatically checked to be committed as well).

This would make it easier to review and commit changes for entire epics or custom issue types (like initiatives)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1876].
  {panel}

In Scope view it is possible to filter out the shown content by only couple of predefined attributes: Projects, Releases, Teams, Contains text, status, Completion Date, Scheduled range, Themes.

In our company we have really complex projects and programs to managed in JIRA and it would be a real MUST to have the possibility to filtering by our custom fields, just like in JIRA. (FC Number, Customers, Request Number, ...)  

